            <p>
              Preparing for international interviews requires some additional steps beyond regular job interviews:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Research the company's culture and the work culture of the country.</li>
              <li>Be prepared to discuss your motivation for relocating and your timeline.</li>
              <li>Practice interviewing across time zones — be flexible with scheduling.</li>
              <li>Highlight any previous international experience or language skills.</li>
              <li>Ask about the visa sponsorship process and relocation package during later interview rounds.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Visit our <a href="/blog/">blog</a> for detailed articles on interview preparation and resume tips for international roles.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {# FAQ 9 #}
      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">Do I need to speak the local language?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>
              It depends on the country and the role. Many tech companies, especially in Northern and Western Europe, operate in English. Countries like the Netherlands, Germany, and the Nordics have a high level of English proficiency in the workplace.
            </p>
            <p>
              However, learning the local language is highly recommended for daily life, social integration, and career advancement. Some countries (like France or Japan) may require local language skills for most positions.
            </p>
            <p>
              Check our <a href="/resources/country-guides/">country guides</a> for language requirements in specific destinations.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {# FAQ 10 #}
      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">How long does visa processing take?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>
              Visa processing times vary significantly depending on the country, visa type, and your nationality. Here are some general estimates:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>EU Blue Card (Germany):</strong> 4–12 weeks</li>
              <li><strong>UK Skilled Worker Visa:</strong> 3–8 weeks</li>
              <li><strong>Canada Express Entry:</strong> 6–12 months (full process)</li>
              <li><strong>US H-1B Visa:</strong> 3–6 months (if selected in lottery)</li>
              <li><strong>Australia Skilled Worker:</strong> 6–18 months</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              We recommend starting the process early and having all documents prepared. Visit our <a href="/resources/visa-information/">visa information page</a> for detailed guidance on different visa types and their requirements.
            </p>
